import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
"53": {
"2": "<p>The Servant grew up before YHWH like a tender shoot and like a root from dry soil. The plant-from-dry-ground image evokes the Davidic stump of Isaiah 11:1 — a surviving root in apparently dead earth. Dry soil connotes the hostile political and spiritual climate: the Babylonian exile was not fertile ground for messianic emergence. The total absence of physical attractiveness is a deliberate anti-royal convention — Samuel's kings (Saul, the young David) were conspicuously handsome; the Servant's emergence bypasses the conventional honor markers of kingship.</p>",
"3": "<p>Despised and rejected by people — a man who knew suffering, familiar with grief. The honor-shame framework of the ANE made public rejection the most devastating social verdict possible. Hiding the face was a ritual act of avoidance: contact with one shamed or ritually impure transferred dishonor. By hiding their faces, the observers treat the Servant as a source of shame-contagion to be avoided rather than a figure to be honored. The community's failure to value him mirrors the exile community's failure to recognize YHWH's work through apparently defeated agents.</p>",
"4": "<p>Yet he was the one who took up our sicknesses and carried our pain. The assumption being corrected — struck down and afflicted by God — was the standard ANE and Israelite medical theology: bodily suffering signaled divine punishment for sin (cf. Job's friends; John 9:2). The Servant's suffering appears to the observers to confirm this logic. The passage then subverts it: the illness and pain are real, but they are ours, not his. The substitutionary transfer is the theological shock.</p>",
"5": "<p>He was pierced because of our transgressions — crushed because of our iniquities. The punishment that brings us peace (<em>shalom</em>) fell on him, and by his wounds we are healed. The verb <em>pierced</em> (<em>meḥolal</em>) refers to a lethal wound. Crushing (<em>daka</em>) implies total destruction. Both are capital-punishment terms. The causal logic is explicit: the transgressions and iniquities are ours; the piercing and crushing are his. The word for wounds (<em>chavurato</em>) denotes the bruised, lacerated wound of flogging — the same punishment as the beating described in 50:6. The healing that results inverts the wound-as-divine-curse logic entirely.</p>",
"6": "<p>We all went astray like sheep — each turned to his own way — and YHWH laid on him the iniquity of us all. The sheep metaphor captures both the innocence and the helplessness of the straying community: sheep do not rebel deliberately but drift away individually. The verb <em>laid on</em> (<em>hifgi'a bo</em>) is the same root used for an intercessor who brings another's case to YHWH — here YHWH himself is both the one who intercedes and the one who bears. The corporate guilt of the entire community is concentrated and transferred to the single figure of the Servant.</p>",
"7": "<p>Oppressed and afflicted, yet he never opened his mouth — like a lamb led to slaughter, like a sheep silent before its shearers. The Passover lamb and wool-industry sheep were both familiar agricultural images. In the ANE, silence before accusers and executioners was not the dignified silence of an innocent man but the political impotence of someone without legal recourse. The Servant's silence is therefore both voluntary and deliberate — not a lack of defense options but a chosen non-response that enables the substitutionary action.</p>",
"8": "<p>By a perversion of justice (<em>oser u-mishpat</em>) he was taken away — cut off from the land of the living, struck for the transgression of my people. The legal irregularity of the proceedings is noted: justice was bent, not applied properly. Being cut off from the land of the living is the Psalmic phrase for execution or untimely death. No official mourning was observed — <em>who gave any thought to his fate</em> implies no lamentation ritual, no proper burial honor, no communal response to his death. The struck-for-others logic is here made explicit by YHWH himself as speaker.</p>",
"9": "<p>He was assigned a grave among the wicked yet his burial was with the rich — though he had done no violence and there was no deceit in his mouth. Executed criminals in the ANE were buried dishonorably, often in mass graves outside the city. The reversal — a rich man's burial — is historically remarkable and treated as significant by the text. The dual innocence declaration (no violence, no deceit) uses the two categories most associated with criminal activity: physical aggression and deceptive speech. The Servant's combination of criminal execution and innocent character produces the paradox the text insists upon.</p>",
"10": "<p>Yet it was YHWH's will to crush him and make him suffer. When his life is given as a guilt offering (<em>asham</em>), he will see his offspring and prolong his days. The <em>asham</em> is the specific sacrificial category of Leviticus 5-6 for unintentional sins requiring both atonement and restitution — distinct from the burnt offering and the sin offering. The guilt offering was brought by the offender to cover the specific damage caused by the violation. Applying this category to the Servant positions him as the sacrifice that covers humanity's specific debt to YHWH. Seeing offspring and prolonging days after death is the resurrection logic embedded in the text.</p>",
"11": "<p>Out of the anguish of his life he will see and be satisfied — by his knowledge my righteous servant will make many righteous and will bear their iniquities. The Servant's own knowledge (<em>da'ato</em>) is the instrument of justification — not merely mechanical sacrifice but the Servant's understanding and deliberate action that makes many righteous. Bearing iniquities is the priestly substitution vocabulary of Leviticus: the priest bore the sin of the community in the atonement ritual. The Servant combines the priestly and sacrificial roles: both the one who offers and the offering itself.</p>",
"12": "<p>Therefore I will give him a portion among the great and he will share the plunder with the strong — because he poured out his life unto death and was counted with the transgressors, for he bore the sin of many and makes intercession for the transgressors. The military-plunder distribution imagery frames the Servant's reward: he receives the share due to a victorious warrior. His being counted with transgressors is the criminal's execution; the intercession for transgressors is an ongoing priestly activity in the present tense. Luke 22:37 explicitly quotes v. 12 as fulfilled at Jesus's crucifixion between two criminals.</p>"
},
"54": {
"1": "<p>Sing for joy, barren woman who has never given birth — for the children of the desolate woman will outnumber the children of the married woman. The barren-woman-who-surpasses pattern runs through Israel's foundational narratives: Sarah (Gen 21:2), Rachel (Gen 30:24), Hannah (1 Sam 1:20). The desolate one producing more children than the one with a husband is an honor-shame inversion: barrenness was the deepest social shame for an ANE woman, and numerical progeny the highest status marker. The desolate one is Zion in exile; the married one is Babylon at the height of her power.</p>",
"2": "<p>Enlarge the space of your tent — stretch out the curtains of your dwelling; lengthen your ropes and drive your tent pegs deeper. Nomadic tent expansion was the immediate consequence of family growth: more children meant more living space, requiring longer guy-ropes staked farther out and more tent panels stitched together. The image combines the domestic intimacy of the Bedouin household with the expansionary logic of covenant blessing. The instruction to enlarge before the children arrive is a command to act in anticipatory faith.</p>",
"3": "<p>For you will spread out to the right and to the left — your descendants will reclaim nations and resettle the ruined cities. Spreading right and left was the directional formula for territorial expansion in ANE treaties (cf. Gen 28:14). Reclaiming nations suggests the returned exiles will not merely inhabit Judah but extend influence to surrounding territories. Resettling ruined cities describes the literal condition of post-587 BCE Judah: the Babylonian campaign left most cities uninhabitable. The oracle promises demographic reversal.</p>",
"4": "<p>Do not be afraid — you will not be put to shame. You will forget the disgrace of your youth and the reproach of your widowhood you will no longer remember. The shame of youth refers to the Egyptian bondage — Israel's period of national infancy as a slave people. The reproach of widowhood is the exile: the death of the husband-king, the destruction of the temple, the cessation of public religious life. Both shame categories are relational and public — they are the community's damaged reputation in the ANE world's honor economy.</p>",
"5": "<p>For your Maker is your husband — YHWH of hosts is his name — and your Redeemer is the Holy One of Israel; he is called the God of the whole earth. The spousal metaphor for YHWH's covenant with Israel recurs through Hosea, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel. Baal worship was literally a rival-husband theology: the Canaanite fertility god as the land's husband who produced agricultural fertility. YHWH reclaims the spousal role with four titles — Maker, YHWH of hosts (divine warrior), Holy One of Israel, God of the whole earth — asserting universal jurisdiction.</p>",
"6": "<p>The LORD has called you back like a wife who was abandoned and heartbroken — like a wife taken in youth and then rejected. In ANE law, the abandoned or divorced wife had limited legal recourse; the initiative for reconciliation had to come from the husband. YHWH's call-back is entirely his own initiative — the wife has not petitioned for return. Being taken in youth but then rejected describes Zion's covenant history: the passionate young relationship of the wilderness period (Hos 2:15) followed by the exile's rejection.</p>",
"7": "<p>For a brief moment I abandoned you, but with great compassion I will bring you back. The temporal contrast — brief moment vs. great compassion — is a covenant proportionality argument. The Babylonian exile (587–539 BCE) was approximately 48 years; YHWH's everlasting love is measured against this. The word for compassion (<em>rahamim</em>) shares its root with <em>rehem</em> (womb): the most visceral, bodily form of parental attachment. Divine compassion is not abstract sentiment but womb-deep maternal love.</p>",
"8": "<p>In a surge of anger I hid my face from you for a moment, but with everlasting covenant love (<em>hesed olam</em>) I will have compassion on you. The hidden face is the withdrawal of the divine presence — the catastrophe of the exile experienced as YHWH's absence rather than his punishment. <em>Hesed olam</em> (everlasting covenant loyalty) is the specific covenantal term for the binding, obligatory love of treaty relationship — not merely affection but the loyalty that the suzerain owes the vassal he has adopted. The moment of anger cannot outlast the everlasting covenant.</p>",
"9": "<p>To me this is like the days of Noah: just as I swore that the waters of Noah would never again cover the earth, so now I swear I will never again be angry with you or rebuke you. The Noahic covenant (Gen 9:11-15) becomes the precedent and model for the new covenant. The rainbow oath was YHWH's self-binding promise to creation; the present oath is YHWH's self-binding promise to Israel. The comparison elevates the covenant-restoration to cosmic proportions: as fundamental as the post-flood guarantee of creation's continuity.</p>",
"10": "<p>Though the mountains should move and the hills be shaken, my covenant love will not move from you, and my covenant of peace will not be shaken. Geological stability was the ANE metaphor for permanence — mountains were the most immovable features of the landscape. By asserting that YHWH's covenant love is more permanent than mountains, the text establishes a stability category beyond geology. The <em>brit shalom</em> (covenant of peace) is the technical term for the comprehensive shalom-relationship of suzerainty, encompassing security, prosperity, and relational wholeness.</p>",
"11": "<p>O afflicted city, tossed by storms and without comfort — I will set your stones in brilliant color and lay your foundations with sapphires. The storm-tossed city image describes the political instability of Jerusalem post-exile: repeatedly conquered, the city lacked the settled permanence of a properly founded civic order. The sapphire foundation invokes the ANE temple-building tradition: great temples were built on cosmic foundations; the new Jerusalem's foundations will be of the most precious cosmic materials.</p>",
"12": "<p>I will make your towers of rubies, your gates of sparkling jewels, and all your walls of precious stones. The precious-stone city vision anticipates Revelation 21:10-21 in remarkable detail. In ANE royal ideology, the elaborate ornamentation of city gates and walls demonstrated the king's wealth and the city's cosmic status. YHWH's rebuilding of Jerusalem exceeds all ANE royal construction projects by using materials that no human builder could afford or source.</p>",
"13": "<p>All your children will be taught by the LORD (<em>limudei YHWH</em>), and great will be their peace. The <em>limudim</em> (disciples/taught ones) root connects to the Servant's discipled tongue of 50:4 and to Isaiah 8:16. The promise that all Zion's children will be YHWH's personal disciples democratizes the prophetic-school relationship. John 6:45 quotes this verse directly as the scriptural basis for being drawn to the Son: everyone taught by YHWH comes to him.</p>",
"14": "<p>You will be established in righteousness — far from oppression and without fear; terror will not come near you. Righteousness (<em>tzedakah</em>) as the foundation of civic order is the standard prophetic vision of the ideal community. The absence of oppression and terror describes the restoration of the Zion ideal: the city where the socially vulnerable are safe, because YHWH's justice is the operating principle of civic life rather than the power calculations of empire.</p>",
"15": "<p>If anyone attacks you it is not my doing — whoever assembles against you will fall before you. The verse addresses the practical concern of the returning exiles: what about enemy attacks? YHWH's disclaimer — <em>it is not my doing</em> — distinguishes unauthorized attacks (which he does not sanction) from the disciplinary exile (which he did). The covenant guarantee of military security for the restored community is here made explicit.</p>",
"16": "<p>I am the one who created the blacksmith who fans the coals and forges a weapon fit for its purpose — and I am the one who created the destroyer to cause ruin. The weapon-creator claim grounds military threat within YHWH's sovereign creation. Even the empire's weapons-industry ultimately traces to YHWH's creative act: the blacksmith is his creature, the forge his provision. No weapon therefore escapes his sovereign authority, making the next verse's promise logically secure.</p>",
"17": "<p>No weapon formed against you will succeed, and every tongue that accuses you in court you will refute. This is the inheritance of YHWH's servants, and their vindication comes from me. The covenant-lawsuit acquittal is permanent: the servants' standing in YHWH's court is established, not provisional. <em>Inheritance</em> (<em>nachalah</em>) is the land-grant term — what YHWH's servants receive as their covenantal portion is not merely protection but vindication that is definitively theirs.</p>"
},
"55": {
"1": "<p>Come, all who are thirsty — come to the waters; you who have no money, come, buy and eat! Come, buy wine and milk without money and without cost (<em>chinnam</em>). The marketplace-crier form was familiar in ANE cities: vendors advertised goods publicly in the open bazaar. The radical inversion is that the best goods — water, wine, milk — are offered <em>chinnam</em> (the same gratis-word as 52:3). Water was precious in the ancient Near East; wine and milk were luxury commodities. The offer of all three without payment overturns the economics of survival and desire simultaneously.</p>",
"2": "<p>Why do you spend money on what is not bread, and your wages on what does not satisfy? The critique targets the Babylonian economy of desire: the exile community spending on food-substitutes (idol-temple feasts, Babylonian religious participation) that provide no genuine nourishment. The metaphor of wages-for-satisfaction is an economic diagnostic — the community is getting a poor return on its spiritual investment. YHWH offers the real commodity (covenant relationship) at no cost while the false goods consume resources.</p>",
"3": "<p>Come, hear, and you will live — and I will make an everlasting covenant with you, the sure mercies I promised to David (<em>hasde david ha-ne'emanim</em>). The Davidic covenant's promised mercies (<em>hesed</em> in the plural = repeated acts of covenant loyalty) are extended beyond the single Davidic king to the entire restored community. This democratization of the Davidic promise is one of Second Isaiah's most significant theological innovations: the covenant benefits that flowed through the royal line are redistributed to the people as a whole.</p>",
"4": "<p>See, I made him a witness to the nations, a leader and commander for the peoples. David's historical role as international figure — the king whose fame spread to surrounding nations — is here repurposed as template for Israel's restored role. The Davidic titles (witness, leader, commander) are conferred on the covenant community in its new-Exodus configuration. Israel becomes the testimony-bearer to the nations in place of the Davidic monarchy.</p>",
"5": "<p>You will summon a nation you did not know, and a nation that did not know you will run to you, because of YHWH your God and the Holy One of Israel, for he has glorified you. The unknown-nation coming to Israel reverses the direction of ANE imperial attraction: normally small nations were drawn to imperial capitals. The ingathering is not because of Israel's inherent attractiveness but because YHWH has glorified her — the divine reputation draws international attention to the restored community.</p>",
"6": "<p>Seek the LORD while he may be found; call on him while he is near. The <em>kairos</em> warning — the appointed time of access is not permanent. This echoes the <em>time of favor</em> (<em>et ratzon</em>) of 49:8: there is a window of divine availability that must be seized. The prophetic tradition consistently insisted that the moment of YHWH's turning toward the people was an opportunity, not a permanent default condition. Missing the window is the tragedy of Israel's recurring covenant failure.</p>",
"7": "<p>Let the wicked forsake his way and the unrighteous man his thoughts; let him return (<em>shuv</em>) to YHWH, who will have compassion on him, and to our God, who will abundantly pardon. The teshuvah (<em>shuv</em> = return/repentance) theology of the prophetic tradition is articulated in its fullest positive form: YHWH will <em>abundantly</em> (<em>yarbe</em>) pardon — multiplicative, not minimal forgiveness. The word <em>pardon</em> (<em>lisloach</em>) is the specific term for covenant amnesty; YHWH's pardon is not reluctant or conditional on adequate contrition but lavishly available.</p>",
"8": "<p>For my thoughts are not your thoughts, and your ways are not my ways, declares YHWH. The incomprehensibility of divine perspective is stated as the theological ground for lavish pardon: human moral accounting would not forgive so freely. The verse connects the abundant pardon of v. 7 to the infinite qualitative gap between divine and human cognition. This is not an evasion of theodicy but an explanation for why YHWH acts in ways that seem logically improbable from within human honor-shame calculus.</p>",
"9": "<p>For as the heavens are higher than the earth, so are my ways higher than your ways and my thoughts than your thoughts. The vertical spatial metaphor for the gap between divine and human cognition uses the most obvious dimension of ANE cosmology: the sky's unreachable height above the land. The heaven-earth axis was the fundamental spatial structure of the ANE worldview, with YHWH located in the highest heaven (<em>shamayim ha-shamayim</em>). His thoughts operate at the level of the highest heaven; human thoughts at the level of dry ground.</p>",
"10": "<p>For as the rain and snow come down from heaven and do not return there until they have watered the earth, making it sprout and bear fruit, giving seed to the farmer and bread to the one who eats. The agricultural water cycle was one of the most carefully observed natural processes in the ancient world: rain fell, watered, produced, fed, and then evaporated back. The cycle was reliable — not random. YHWH's word has this same invariable efficacy: it does not return empty any more than precipitation returns without having watered.</p>",
"11": "<p>So shall my word be that goes out from my mouth — it shall not return to me empty but shall accomplish what I intend and succeed in what I send it to do. The divine word as active agent is a consistent Isaianic theme: the word sent on a mission (cf. 9:8 — a word sent against Jacob). Here the word's efficacy is guaranteed by the precipitation analogy. In ANE theology, divine decrees and royal edicts were self-executing — the great king's word created the reality it described. YHWH's word operates at this level but without the failures that occasionally undercut royal decrees.</p>",
"12": "<p>For you will go out with joy and be led forth in peace — the mountains and the hills shall burst into song before you, and all the trees of the field shall clap their hands. The cosmic celebration of the new Exodus mirrors Isaiah 49:13 and the Psalms of creation-praise. Mountains singing and trees clapping are the natural world joining the covenant celebration. The RSV-familiar image of nature's joy is an ANE hymnic convention: creation praises YHWH's victories by personified rejoicing. The joyful, peaceful departure contrasts with the haste-and-fear of the Egyptian Exodus.</p>",
"13": "<p>Instead of the thorn the cypress shall come up, and instead of the brier the myrtle shall come up — a memorial to YHWH, an everlasting sign that will never be cut off. The vegetation reversal (thorn → cypress, brier → myrtle) is the Eden-restoration pattern: the curse-vegetation of Genesis 3:18 gives way to the fragrant, useful trees of the renewed creation. The myrtle (<em>hadas</em>) was a ceremonial plant in Israel (Neh 8:15; Zech 1:8-11). The reversal becomes a permanent covenant sign embedded in the landscape.</p>"
},
"56": {
"1": "<p>Thus says YHWH: Maintain justice and do what is right, for my salvation is coming soon and my righteousness is about to be revealed. The ethical imperative precedes the eschatological promise: keeping mishpat and doing righteousness are the conditions of the covenant community's life, not prerequisites for earning the salvation. The salvation is already coming; the ethical life is the appropriate response to and participation in the approaching divine act.</p>",
"2": "<p>Blessed is the man who does this and the person who holds to it — who keeps the sabbath without profaning it and refrains from doing any evil. Sabbath-keeping as the visible covenantal marker was the distinctive practice of the exilic and post-exilic community. In Babylon, where the temple calendar was impossible to maintain, the sabbath became the portable covenant sign — the one practice that identified Israel as YHWH's covenant people without requiring land, temple, or king.</p>",
"3": "<p>Let not the foreigner who has joined himself to YHWH say, 'The LORD will surely exclude me from his people'; and let not the eunuch say, 'I am a withered tree.' The two excluded categories of Deuteronomy 23:1, 3-8 — eunuchs (v. 1) and certain foreigners (Ammonites/Moabites, vv. 3-8) — are explicitly addressed. The foreigner's fear of exclusion and the eunuch's self-identification as a withered tree (no biological legacy) represent the shame of the marginalized. The oracle overturns both exclusions.</p>",
"4": "<p>To the eunuchs who keep my sabbaths, who choose what pleases me and hold fast to my covenant — the criteria for inclusion shift entirely from biological status to ethical and covenantal practice: sabbath-keeping, choosing YHWH's will, holding the covenant. Eunuchs in ANE royal courts (Babylon, Persia, Assyria) were often powerful administrators and confidants of the king; the Daniel narrative operates in this environment. Their exclusion from the covenant assembly despite their importance in imperial service is addressed here.</p>",
"5": "<p>I will give them within my house and within my walls a memorial and a name (<em>yad va-shem</em>, literally hand and name) better than sons and daughters — an everlasting name that will never be cut off. The <em>yad va-shem</em> (hand and name, the phrase from which Yad Vashem draws its name) provides the eunuch with permanent covenant memorial in place of biological legacy. Sons and daughters were the normal vehicle for name-perpetuation in the ANE; the eunuch who cannot have biological children receives a name that outlasts all biological lineages.</p>",
"6": "<p>The foreigners who join themselves to YHWH, to serve him, to love the name of YHWH, and to be his servants — everyone who keeps the sabbath without profaning it and holds fast my covenant. The three criteria for the foreigner's full inclusion — service, love of the name, sabbath-keeping — are identical to what is asked of the native Israelite. The covenant community is redefined around practice and commitment rather than genealogy, anticipating the full Gentile inclusion of the New Testament.</p>",
"7": "<p>Even them I will bring to my holy mountain and make them glad in my house of prayer; their burnt offerings and sacrifices will be accepted on my altar — for my house shall be called a house of prayer for all peoples. The temple's purpose as a house of prayer for all peoples is the most universalist statement in the Hebrew Bible's temple theology. The temple was constructed with zones of exclusion (Court of Women, Court of Israel, Court of Priests) that kept non-Israelites at a distance. Jesus quotes this verse (Mark 11:17; Matt 21:13) when cleansing the temple — invoking its original intention against its corrupted present practice.</p>",
"8": "<p>The Lord YHWH, who gathers the outcasts of Israel, declares: I will gather yet others to him besides those already gathered to him. The progressive ingathering: the restoration of the scattered Israelites is not the endpoint but the penultimate stage. Beyond the gathered Israelites, YHWH will gather yet more — the foreigner and eunuch of vv. 3-6 are the initial examples, but the <em>others</em> gestures toward a gathering that exceeds ethnic Israel. This is the open horizon of Second Isaiah's universalism.</p>",
"9": "<p>All you wild animals of the field, come to devour — all you beasts of the forest. The sudden shift to an invitation to predators signals a judgment oracle against Israel's failed leaders (vv. 10-12). In ANE treaty and prophetic literature, wild animals devouring a flock signaled the complete failure of shepherds to protect their charges. The invitation to the beasts is ironic: since the watchmen have failed, the natural predators may as well come.</p>",
"10": "<p>Israel's watchmen are all blind; none of them understand. They are all silent dogs that cannot bark — they dream, lie down, and love to sleep. The watchmen on city walls were the first line of warning against approaching enemies; the dogs patrolling at night barked at intruders. Both failures are catastrophic: blind watchmen and mute dogs leave the community undefended. The critique targets the prophetic and priestly leadership of the exile period — those who should have warned, interpreted events, and led the community's response have instead retreated into passivity.</p>",
"11": "<p>The dogs are ravenous — never satisfied; and the shepherds have no understanding; they have all gone their own way, each after his own profit. The ravenous-dog image intensifies the critique: not merely lazy but actively self-seeking. The shepherd-for-profit trope is Ezekiel 34's theme throughout — the shepherds who feed themselves rather than the flock. The combination of pastoral failure (no understanding) and economic corruption (pursuing profit) describes a leadership class that has inverted its covenant obligations.</p>",
"12": "<p>Come, they say, let us get wine; let us fill ourselves with strong drink — and tomorrow will be like today, even more abundant. The carpe diem materialism of the corrupt leaders — drinking today, confident tomorrow will bring more — is the ancient world's version of fatalistic hedonism. The phrase <em>tomorrow will be like today, even more abundant</em> captures an attitude of complacency that dismisses prophetic warning about coming judgment. Isaiah 22:13 uses similar language for Jerusalem's pre-siege revelry.</p>"
},
"57": {
"1": "<p>The righteous man perishes and no one takes it to heart — faithful men are taken away and no one understands. The righteous man is taken away from the evil to come. Social obliviousness to the deaths of the godly is a recurring prophetic complaint: the community fails to read the departure of the righteous as a sign. The phrase <em>taken away from the evil to come</em> interprets the righteous person's early death as providential rescue — they are removed before the coming judgment arrives, a mercy misread as tragedy.</p>",
"2": "<p>He enters into peace — they rest in their resting places, each one who walked uprightly. The righteous person's death as entry into <em>shalom</em> is an early formulation of afterlife hope: the upright dead are in a state of rest rather than the anxious unresolved condition of those who die under judgment. The resting places are not merely graves but a condition of settled covenantal security beyond death.</p>",
"3": "<p>But you — come here, you children of the sorceress, offspring of the adulterer and the prostitute. The diatribe shifts abruptly to the syncretistic community. Sorceress, adulterer, and prostitute are not merely moral categories but describe the three dimensions of Israel's covenant apostasy: sorcery (divination, seeking knowledge outside YHWH), adultery (the covenant faithlessness toward YHWH as husband), and prostitution (hiring out covenant loyalty to foreign powers and their gods in exchange for political security).</p>",
"4": "<p>Whom are you mocking? Against whom do you open your mouth wide and stick out your tongue? Are you not children of rebellion, the offspring of lies? Mouth-opening and tongue-extension were ANE gestures of contempt and defiance. The mocking target is implicitly YHWH and his prophets. The designation <em>children of rebellion</em> (<em>yalde pesha</em>) and <em>offspring of lies</em> frames the idolatrous community's identity as constituted by their apostasy — they are what they practice.</p>",
"5": "<p>You who inflame yourselves among the trees, under every leafy tree — who slaughter children in the ravines, under the crevices of the rocks. The high-place fertility cult worship under trees was the standard description of Canaanite religious practice that Israel adopted (Deut 12:2; Hos 4:13). Child sacrifice in the valley of Hinnom (Topheth) is the specific horror alluded to — burning children as offerings to Molech (2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 7:31). The rocky crevices as sacrifice sites suggest remote locations for hidden cult activity.</p>",
"6": "<p>Your lot is among the smooth stones of the streambeds — they are your portion; you have poured out drink offerings to them and brought grain offerings. Should I be appeased by these things? The smooth stones of streambeds may represent the <em>masseboth</em> (standing stones) used in Canaanite shrine practice, or specific deity-stones associated with stream deities. Pouring libations and presenting grain offerings to rocks is the direct inversion of covenant worship: the correct offerings redirected to non-entities. YHWH's rhetorical question expects the answer: no.</p>",
"7": "<p>On a high and lofty mountain you set your bed — you went up there to offer sacrifice. The bed on the high mountain combines the spatial location of the Baalist high places with the sexual imagery of covenant apostasy as adultery. Going up to offer sacrifice on elevated terrain was the standard Canaanite cultic practice that prophets consistently condemned as the alternative to YHWH's centralized worship.</p>",
"8": "<p>Behind the door and the doorpost you placed your memorial — away from me you uncovered yourself, spread your bed wide, and struck a deal with them; you loved their bed and looked upon what was exposed. The doorpost memorial inverts the Passover sign (mezuzah) that YHWH commanded: instead of his name on the doorpost, an idol. The uncovering, bed-spreading, and deal-making sustain the adultery metaphor: covenant apostasy is a sexual relationship with the idols rather than YHWH.</p>",
"9": "<p>You traveled to the king with oil and multiplied your fragrances — you sent your messengers far off, even down to Sheol. Traveling to the king with tribute oil was the standard ANE diplomatic protocol for vassal acknowledgment of a suzerain. Whether the king is a foreign power (Assyria, Babylon, Egypt) or the deity Molech, Israel has substituted a false suzerain for YHWH. The messengers sent even to Sheol — the underworld — suggests necromantic consultation: seeking guidance from the dead rather than YHWH (cf. Isa 8:19; 1 Sam 28).</p>",
"10": "<p>You grew weary from your many journeys but you did not say, 'It is hopeless' — you found renewed strength, and so you were not weak. The tireless pursuit of idolatry despite the exhaustion it produces is the image of addiction: the spiritual energy invested in false worship renews itself because the idolater has found (false) vitality in it. This is different from the renewal of strength YHWH promises (40:31) — the idol worshiper's renewal is the self-sustaining energy of a destructive habit.</p>",
"11": "<p>Whom did you fear and dread, that you lied and did not remember me or call it to mind? Was it not because I was silent and looked away that you have not feared me? YHWH's silence during the exile period was interpreted by the apostates as his permanent absence or impotence. The divine non-intervention that seemed to validate the idol-worship was actually YHWH's patience. His silence was mistaken for consent; his looking away was mistaken for defeat.</p>",
"12": "<p>I will expose your righteousness and your deeds — but they will not benefit you. The ironic <em>your righteousness</em> (<em>tzidkatekh</em>) refers to the formal religious practice the community considers meritorious — their temple-cult performances and idol-worship — which YHWH will expose as the sham it is. The moral inventory of ANE legal proceedings exposed the defendant's deeds before the judge; here YHWH conducts that examination and finds the self-styled righteousness worthless.</p>",
"13": "<p>When you cry out, let your collection of idols rescue you — the wind will carry them all off, a breath will sweep them away. But whoever takes refuge in me will possess the land and inherit my holy mountain. The wind-dispersal of idols is the anti-idol polemic's most devastating image: the gods you trusted cannot even maintain their own stability against a breeze. The pivot in the second half of the verse establishes the alternative: those who take refuge in YHWH receive the inheritance that the idol-worshipers will lose — land and holy mountain.</p>",
"14": "<p>A voice will say: Build up, build up, prepare the way — clear every obstruction from the road for my people. The highway-preparation command recapitulates 40:3-4 and 62:10. The road-clearing for the returning exiles was the standard royal infrastructure task in the ANE: great kings cleared, leveled, and maintained roads for processions and military movements. YHWH's highway-preparation surpasses all royal road-building because it removes every obstacle for the covenant community's return.</p>",
"15": "<p>For thus says the One who is high and lifted up, who inhabits eternity, whose name is Holy: I dwell in the high and holy place, and also with the one who has a contrite and humble spirit, to revive the spirit of the humble and to revive the heart of the contrite. The divine paradox of simultaneous transcendence and immanence: YHWH inhabits eternity in the highest cosmic space AND dwells with the crushed (<em>daka</em>) and lowly of spirit. The word <em>contrite</em> shares a root with the Servant's crushing in 53:5 — YHWH specifically inhabits the space of the shattered.</p>",
"16": "<p>For I will not contend forever, nor will I be angry forever — for the spirit would faint before me and the breath of life that I have created. Divine anger is self-limiting not because of its weakness but because of the fragility of its object. If YHWH's anger were permanent and total, the created spirits he has made would disintegrate: they cannot survive unrelenting divine wrath. The restraint of judgment is therefore an act of preservation consistent with YHWH's creator role.</p>",
"17": "<p>Because of the iniquity of his greed I was angry; I struck him; I hid my face and was angry — but he kept going, backsliding along the way of his own heart. The hidden-face withdrawal of divine presence did not produce repentance but escalating apostasy. The pattern — discipline → continued sin — is the diagnosis of the exile community's spiritual condition. YHWH struck, hid his face, and the people simply continued on their own path: the discipline did not achieve its corrective purpose.</p>",
"18": "<p>I have seen his ways, yet I will heal him — I will lead him and restore comfort to him and to those who mourn with him. Divine healing despite observed waywardness is the covenant mercy that transcends the principle of proportional response. YHWH sees the backsliding (v. 17) and responds not with further punishment but with healing. The <em>leading</em> and <em>comforting</em> are shepherding actions: YHWH as the good shepherd who retrieves the wandering flock rather than abandoning them to their own path.</p>",
"19": "<p>Creating the fruit of the lips — peace, peace, to the far and to the near, says YHWH, and I will heal them. YHWH creates speech — the <em>fruit of the lips</em> — as an act parallel to his creation of the physical world. The double <em>shalom shalom</em> (peace, peace) is the emphatic doubled blessing: comprehensive covenant wellbeing extended to both those near (the returned exiles) and those far (the diaspora still scattered). Ephesians 2:17 quotes this verse as fulfilled in Christ: he <em>preached peace to those far away and peace to those who were near.</em></p>",
"20": "<p>But the wicked are like the churning sea — it cannot be still, and its waters stir up mire and mud. The chaos-sea imagery recurs from 51:9-10 but now applied to the wicked within the community: they have the inner agitation of the restless deep, unable to achieve the <em>shalom</em> promised to the humble and contrite. The churning that produces mire and mud is the moral pollution generated by the absence of covenant peace.</p>",
"21": "<p>There is no peace, says my God, for the wicked. The refrain appears at 48:22 and here at 57:21, forming a deliberate structural bracket around the central section of chapters 49–57. The <em>no peace for the wicked</em> declaration is not a threat of future punishment but a present diagnosis: the covenantal condition of <em>shalom</em> is structurally unavailable to those who reject the covenant. Peace is not a reward withheld; it is the natural consequence of covenant relationship that the wicked have excluded themselves from.</p>"
},
"58": {
"1": "<p>Cry out loudly — do not hold back; raise your voice like a trumpet and tell my people their rebellion and the house of Jacob their sins. The shofar (trumpet) was used for covenant assembly, alarm, and proclamation. Using the prophetic voice like a trumpet signals that what follows is a formal covenant-lawsuit indictment (<em>rib</em>). The paradox established immediately: the community being indicted considers itself righteously observant. Calling it <em>my people</em> while indicting them maintains the covenant relationship while naming its violation.</p>",
"2": "<p>Yet day after day they seek me and are eager to know my ways — as though they were a nation that practices righteousness and has not abandoned the law of their God; they ask of me just decrees and are pleased to draw near to God. The devastating description of sincere-seeming religious performance without ethical content. The seeking, eagerness, and pleasure in drawing near are genuine emotional states — this is not cynical hypocrisy but sincere religiosity disconnected from justice. They ask for just decrees while practicing injustice; the disconnection is not noticed from inside the practice.</p>",
"3": "<p>They say, 'Why have we fasted but you do not notice? Why have we denied ourselves and you take no account of it?' Look — on your fast day you pursue your own interests and push all your laborers. The Day of Atonement fast (and other prescribed fast days) required economic suspension: no work, no commerce. But the people are using the fast day to press their laborers for productivity — the <em>denial of self</em> is performed religiously while economic exploitation continues. YHWH notices the fast and the exploitation simultaneously.</p>",
"4": "<p>Look, you fast only to quarrel and brawl and to strike with a wicked fist. You cannot fast as you do today and expect your voice to be heard on high. The social violence accompanying the fasting nullifies the fasting's religious efficacy: the acts of worship are performed alongside the acts of oppression. ANE prayer and sacrifice were understood to be heard by the deity when performed in the correct ritual manner; YHWH declares that no ritual correctness can make audible a prayer accompanied by violence against the vulnerable.</p>",
"5": "<p>Is this the kind of fast I have chosen — merely a day for people to deny themselves, to bow their heads like a reed and spread sackcloth and ashes beneath them? Is that what you call a fast, a day acceptable to the LORD? The reed-bowing posture and sackcloth-and-ashes are the standard ANE and Israelite penitential gestures. YHWH's question is not rhetorical rejection of ritual form but exposure of form without content: the posture of repentance without the reorientation of power toward justice is theater, not worship.</p>",
"6": "<p>Is not this the fast I choose: to release the bonds of injustice, to untie the ropes of the yoke, to set the oppressed free, and to break every yoke? The Jubilee fast — the Day of Atonement of Leviticus 25 announced the Jubilee year of release — is the template here: debt-slavery release, oppression freedom, yoke-breaking. YHWH's chosen fast is an economic and social event, not merely a personal religious exercise. The verbal cluster (release, untie, set free, break) is liberation vocabulary.</p>",
"7": "<p>Is it not to share your food with the hungry, to bring the wandering poor into your home, to clothe the naked when you see them, and not to look away from your own kin? The three acts of practical justice — food-sharing, housing the displaced, clothing the naked — constitute the authentic fast. <em>Not looking away from your own kin</em> is the covenant obligation of family solidarity extended to the community: the poor neighbor is <em>flesh</em> (<em>basar</em>) — literally bodily kin. Averting the eyes from need is itself a covenant violation.</p>",
"8": "<p>Then your light will break out like the dawn and your recovery will come quickly — your righteousness will lead the way before you, and the glory of the LORD will be your rear guard. The light-at-dawn metaphor captures the sudden, unmistakable appearance of covenant blessing after the darkness of injustice. The rear guard is YHWH's glory — the same pillar of cloud and fire that protected Israel at the Exodus (Exod 14:19-20). The new-Exodus pattern: covenant justice produces the divine presence that led and protected the first Exodus community.</p>",
"9": "<p>Then you will call and YHWH will answer — you will cry and he will say, 'Here I am' (<em>hineni</em>). If you remove the yoke from among you, stop the pointing finger, and stop speaking wickedness. The <em>hineni</em> (here I am) is the divine response to the human call — the covenant call-and-answer restored. The pointing finger (<em>shalach etzba</em>) describes the condescending gesture of accusation or contempt toward the vulnerable: the social habit of marking others as inferior or culpable. Removing it is part of dismantling the oppressive social structure the fast was masking.</p>",
"10": "<p>If you give yourself to the hungry and satisfy the needs of the oppressed — then your light will rise in the darkness and your deepest night will become as bright as noon. The self-giving (<em>tafiq le-ra'ev nafshekha</em> — literally pour out your soul to the hungry) is the extreme form of food-sharing: not giving from surplus but from the self. The darkness-to-noon reversal describes the exile's darkness being illuminated by justice — the ethical act produces the eschatological transformation.</p>",
"11": "<p>The LORD will guide you continually and satisfy you in dry places and strengthen your bones — you will be like a well-watered garden, like a spring whose waters never run dry. The wilderness-provision imagery (guidance in dry places, satisfaction when parched) recapitulates the Exodus experience as template for the restored community's life. The well-watered garden is Eden-language; the spring that never runs dry is the covenant relationship's inexhaustible provision. Dry places that become gardens is the reversal at the heart of all Second Isaiah's restoration promises.</p>",
"12": "<p>Your people will rebuild the ancient ruins — you will raise up the foundations of many generations; you will be called the Repairer of the Breach (<em>Goder Peres</em>), the Restorer of Paths to Live In (<em>Meshovev Netivot</em>). The specific titles — Repairer of the Breach and Restorer of Paths — are covenant-restoration functions. The breach (<em>peres</em>) in a city wall represented the point of maximum vulnerability and the evidence of defeat. Repairing it restored defensibility and honor simultaneously. Restoring paths is infrastructure repair that enables community life. The community that practices justice inherits these constructive roles.</p>",
"13": "<p>If you keep your feet from breaking the Sabbath and refrain from doing as you please on my holy day — if you call the Sabbath a delight and the LORD's holy day worthy of honor; if you honor it by not following your own ways or pursuing your own pleasures or talking idly. The Sabbath oracle closes the chapter by returning to the covenantal marker of identity. The multiple negatives — not breaking, not doing own pleasure, not talking idly — define Sabbath as the structured suspension of self-will. The positive reframing as <em>delight</em> (<em>oneg</em>) is the distinctive Isaianic contribution: Sabbath is not merely obligation but joy.</p>",
"14": "<p>Then you will find your joy in the LORD, and I will make you ride on the heights of the earth — I will nourish you with the heritage of Jacob your father, for the mouth of the LORD has spoken. Riding on the heights of the earth is the dominion imagery of Deuteronomy 32:13 — YHWH making Israel ride the high places of the land in the conquest. The heritage of Jacob is the patriarchal land-promise in its fullest form. The oracle closes with the prophetic authentication formula (<em>ki pi YHWH diber</em>) — the mouth of YHWH has spoken — marking the promise as irrevocable.</p>"
}
}

